---
const title = 'How to Cite a Website in APA Format (2025 Guide)';
const description =
	'Learn how to cite any website in APA 7th edition format. Free examples, templates, and our instant citation generator.';
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
	<head>
		<meta charset="UTF-8" />
		<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
		<meta name="description" content={description} />
		<meta name="robots" content="index, follow" />
		<link rel="icon" type="image/svg+xml" href="/favicon.svg" />
		<link rel="icon" href="/favicon.ico" />
		<meta name="generator" content={Astro.generator} />
		<title>{title} — StudyKit</title>
	</head>
	<body>
		<div class="page">
			<header class="header">
				<a href="/" class="brand">
					<span class="brand-icon" aria-hidden="true">📚</span>
					<span class="brand-name">StudyKit</span>
				</a>
				<p class="article-meta">APA Guides · Updated for 2025</p>
				<h1>How to Cite a Website in APA Format (2025 Guide)</h1>
				<p class="subtitle">
					A clear, step-by-step walkthrough of APA 7th edition website citations — with real examples you can copy and adapt.
				</p>
			</header>

			<main class="main">
				<article class="card article">
					<p>
						Whether you are writing a psychology paper, a nursing case study, or a business report, you will
						almost certainly need to cite online sources. Websites are among the most common references students
						use — and among the most frequently formatted incorrectly. APA 7th edition changed several rules
						from earlier versions, so if you learned APA 6 in high school, some of what you remember no longer
						applies.
					</p>
					<p>
						This guide explains exactly how to cite a website in APA format: what information you need, where
						each piece goes, and how to handle tricky situations like missing authors or undated pages. By the
						end, you will be able to build a correct reference entry from scratch — or skip the manual work
						entirely with a citation generator.
					</p>

					<h2>What APA 7 Requires for Website Citations</h2>
					<p>
						In APA style, a website citation appears on your <strong>References</strong> page (not in the body
						of your paper — that is an in-text citation, which follows different rules). A complete reference
						entry for a standalone web page includes up to five core elements, in this order:
					</p>
					<ol class="steps-list">
						<li><strong>Author</strong> — the person or organization responsible for the content</li>
						<li><strong>Date</strong> — the publication or last-updated date, in parentheses</li>
						<li><strong>Title</strong> — the title of the specific page (not the whole website)</li>
						<li><strong>Source</strong> — the name of the website, in italics</li>
						<li><strong>URL</strong> — a live link, with no "Retrieved from" prefix</li>
					</ol>
					<p>
						Unlike APA 6, APA 7 no longer requires "Retrieved from" before a URL, and you generally do not
						need a retrieval date unless the content is designed to change over time (such as a wiki or a
						live data dashboard). For most news articles, government pages, and educational resources, the
						publication date alone is sufficient.
					</p>

					<h2>Step-by-Step: Building Your APA Website Citation</h2>
					<p>
						Follow these steps every time you cite a web page. Gather the information first, then assemble it
						using the template below.
					</p>

					<h3>Step 1: Identify the Author</h3>
					<p>
						Look for a byline at the top of the page. The author may be an individual (e.g., "Jane Smith")
						or an organization (e.g., "World Health Organization"). Format individual authors as
						<em>Last name, First initial. Middle initial.</em> — for example, <em>Smith, J. A.</em> For
						organizational authors, spell out the full name: <em>World Health Organization.</em>
					</p>
					<p>
						If there is no identifiable author, skip the author element and start the reference with the page
						title instead (see Example 3 below). Do not use "Anonymous" unless the source itself explicitly
						lists Anonymous as the author.
					</p>

					<h3>Step 2: Find the Date</h3>
					<p>
						Search the page for a publication date, "Posted on," "Last updated," or copyright year in the
						footer. Write the date inside parentheses immediately after the author, followed by a period.
						Use the most specific date available:
					</p>
					<ul>
						<li>Full date: <em>(2024, March 15)</em></li>
						<li>Year and month only: <em>(2024, March)</em></li>
						<li>Year only: <em>(2024)</em></li>
					</ul>
					<p>
						If no date appears anywhere, use <em>(n.d.)</em> for "no date." Never guess a year — instructors
						and reviewers can verify dates, and an incorrect year counts as an error.
					</p>

					<h3>Step 3: Write the Page Title</h3>
					<p>
						Use the title of the specific page you are citing, not the homepage title of the entire site.
						Capitalize it using sentence case: capitalize only the first word, the first word after a colon,
						and proper nouns. Do not italicize the page title. End with a period.
					</p>
					<p>
						For example, if you are citing a CDC fact sheet, the title might be
						<em>About chronic diseases</em> — not <em>Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</em>, which
						is the site name.
					</p>

					<h3>Step 4: Add the Website Name (Source)</h3>
					<p>
						After the page title, write the name of the website in italics. This is often the same as the
						organizational author, and that is fine — repeat it. For example, a CDC page lists both the author
						and source as <em>Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</em>. End with a period.
					</p>

					<h3>Step 5: Include the URL</h3>
					<p>
						Paste the full, direct URL to the page — not the homepage, unless that is what you actually read.
						Do not add a period after the URL. APA 7 prefers stable links; if the source provides a DOI for
						web content, use the DOI instead of the URL when one is available.
					</p>

					<div class="template-box" role="note" aria-label="APA website citation template">
						<p class="template-label">APA 7 Website Citation Template</p>
						<p class="template-formula">
							Author, A. A. (Year, Month Day). <span class="plain">Title of page.</span>
							<em> Name of Website.</em> URL
						</p>
					</div>

					<h2>Three Real APA Website Citation Examples</h2>
					<p>
						These examples follow APA 7th edition rules. Notice how each handles a slightly different
						situation — individual author, organization author, and no author.
					</p>

					<h3>Example 1: Online News Article with an Individual Author</h3>
					<p class="example-context">
						Source: An NPR health article by a named journalist, published June 12, 2023.
					</p>
					<div class="example-box">
						<p>
							Davis, K. (2023, June 12). How sleep deprivation affects memory and learning. <em>NPR</em>.
							https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2023/06/12/1181234567/how-sleep-deprivation-affects-memory
						</p>
					</div>

					<h3>Example 2: Government Website with an Organization as Author</h3>
					<p class="example-context">
						Source: A CDC information page updated March 15, 2024. The organization is both author and site name.
					</p>
					<div class="example-box">
						<p>
							Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. (2024, March 15). About chronic diseases.
							<em>Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</em>.
							https://www.cdc.gov/chronicdisease/about/index.htm
						</p>
					</div>

					<h3>Example 3: Web Page with No Author</h3>
					<p class="example-context">
						Source: A Federal Student Aid page with no listed author. The reference begins with the page title.
					</p>
					<div class="example-box">
						<p>
							How to apply for financial aid. (2025, January 8). <em>Federal Student Aid</em>.
							https://studentaid.gov/apply-for-aid
						</p>
					</div>

					<h2>Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
					<p>
						Even experienced writers slip up on website citations. Watch out for these frequent errors:
					</p>
					<ul>
						<li>
							<strong>Using the website homepage URL</strong> when you read a specific article or subpage.
							Always link to the exact page you referenced.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong>Italicizing the page title</strong> instead of the website name. Only the source (site
							name) gets italics in a web page reference.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong>Adding "Retrieved from"</strong> before the URL. APA 7 dropped this phrase for most
							sources.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong>Listing "Anonymous"</strong> when no author is shown. Start with the title instead.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong>Mixing up in-text and reference formats.</strong> In-text citations use author and year
							only — e.g., (Davis, 2023) — while the reference list entry includes the full details above.
						</li>
					</ul>

					<h2>In-Text Citations for Websites</h2>
					<p>
						Your References page is only half the job. Every source you cite must also appear in the body of
						your paper. For a website with an author, use the author-date format: (Davis, 2023). For a page
						with no author, use a shortened version of the title in quotation marks: ("How to Apply," 2025).
						For organization authors, use the abbreviation after the first citation if one is well known — e.g.,
						(Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC], 2024), then (CDC, 2024).
					</p>

					<h2>Quick Checklist Before You Submit</h2>
					<p>Run through this list before adding a website citation to your References page:</p>
					<ul class="checklist">
						<li>Author formatted correctly (last name, initials) or title leading the entry if no author</li>
						<li>Date in parentheses — specific as possible, or (n.d.) if truly unavailable</li>
						<li>Page title in sentence case, not italicized</li>
						<li>Website name in italics</li>
						<li>Full, direct URL with no trailing period</li>
						<li>Hanging indent applied on your References page (standard APA formatting)</li>
					</ul>
				</article>

				<section class="card cta-card" aria-labelledby="cta-heading">
					<h2 id="cta-heading">Generate Your Citation in Seconds</h2>
					<p>
						Manual formatting works, but it is slow — especially when you are juggling ten or more sources.
						StudyKit's free APA Citation Generator builds website, book, and journal citations for you. Enter
						your source details, click generate, and copy a ready-to-paste reference formatted to APA 7th
						edition standards.
					</p>
					<a href="/" class="btn btn-primary">Try the Free APA Citation Generator</a>
				</section>
			</main>

			<footer class="footer">
				<p>&copy; {new Date().getFullYear()} StudyKit — Free tools for students.</p>
			</footer>
		</div>
	</body>
</html>

